1. This is illuſtrated in Gaal and his brethren, Judg. 9.27, 28. who in the houſe of their Elohims eat and drink; 
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               , and made light of Abimelech, or blaſphemed Abimelech, ſaying thus: Who is Abimelech, or who is Shechem, that we ſhould ſerve him? is be not the ſon of Jerubbaal, and Zebul his officer? Serve the men of Hamor, and the father of Shechem; for why ſhould we ſerve him? Verſ. 29. Would to God this people were under my hand, then would I remove Abimelech. Note well, he vilifies Abimelech, to ſet up himſelf in his place onely. A thing natural, ariſing out of an unſound heart to God.
